definition.value: A form of oppression that occurs due to race and gender. It is perpetuated due to the prevalence of perceptions, stereotypes, and images of certain groups.
The discrimination and subordination of a particular sex in academic institutions, particularly universities, due to the ideologies, practices and reinforcements that privilege one sex over another.

The internalization of assumptions, negative attitudes and stigma regarding homosexuality by individuals whom do not identify within the heteronormative spectrum and/or are categorized as sexual minorities to varying degrees.
Sexism that occurs on an individual level. Internalized sexism is when an individual enacts learned sexist behaviors and attitudes towards themselves and people of their own sex.
The act of identifying as a man and discriminating against oneself and one's masculinity.
The act of identifying as a woman and discriminating against oneself and one's femininity.
The hatred of, contempt for, or prejudice against transgender women in general.
Any discriminatory practices, statements, actions, etc., based on a person's gender and/or sex that are present or occur in a place of employment.
Prejudice based on one's status as LGBTQIA+.
A surgical procedure in which the thyroid cartilage is enlarged and masculinized to enhance the laryngeal prominence (the Adam's Apple).
A surgical procedure in which the thyroid cartilage is feminized, typically by reducing the size of the laryngeal prominence (the Adam's Apple).

A surgical procedure in which the thyroid cartilage is reduced in size by shaving down the cartilage through an incision in the throat, generally to aid those who are uncomfortable with the girth of their laryngeal prominence (Adam's apple).
A specific phobia that involves a fear caused by the presence or thought of a specific animal that poses little or no danger at all.
Any specific phobia involving some negative experience or experiences, such as the fear of the dark or the fear of small confined spaces.
A specific phobia involving some aspect of the environment, such as the fear of heights or the fear of water.

A range of negative attitudes and feelings toward homosexuality and gay people. It has been defined as contempt, prejudice, aversion, hatred or antipathy, may be based on irrational fear and ignorance, and is often related to religious beliefs.
Homophobia is sometimes used as a "catch-all" term for forms of LGBTQIA+ prejudice.

In the 1990s, behavioral scientists William O'Donohue and Christine Caselles argued that the term homophobia was pejorative. In 2012, the Associated Press Stylebook was revised to advise against using -phobia words in non-clinical ways, and AP editor Dave Minthorn suggested replacing "homophobic" with "anti-gay".
Fear of, dislike of or prejudice against transgender people.

An aversion toward bisexuality and toward bisexual people as a social group or as individuals. It can take the form of denial that bisexuality is a genuine sexual orientation, or of negative stereotypes about people who are bisexual (such as the beliefs that they are promiscuous or dishonest).

Various forms of negativity towards lesbians as individuals, as couples, or as a social group. Based on the categories of sex, sexual orientation, identity, and gender expression, this negativity encompasses prejudice, discrimination, hatred, and abuse; with attitudes and feelings ranging from disdain to hostility. Lesbophobia is misogyny that intersects with homophobia, and vice versa.
Homophobia against oneself supposedly caused by one's own repressed homosexuality.
Surgery performed on the ear and its parts, the nose and nasal cavity, or the throat, including surgery of the adenoids, tonsils, pharynx, and trachea.
Transphobia against oneself supposedly caused by one's own repressed transgender identity.

Transphobia within neopagan communities, related closely to radical feminist transphobia. It is eespecially common in Dianic Wiccan circles, and transgender women have been excluded from events at nominally ecumenical neopagan gatherings.

Transphobia which makes exceptions for transgender people deemed "trans enough" or who have had mostly successful outward transitions in terms of "expected" gender presentation. It makes a distinction between "true" transgender people and "transtrenders", persons who are supposedly only pretending to be trans as a modern fad.
Fear, dislike, or hatred of asexual people and/or human asexuality.
Discrimination based on one's sexual behavior, sexuality, or other sexual characteristics.
Discrimination against, opposition of, or hostility towards any or all sexual behavior and sexuality.
Prejudice based on one's sexuality.
Fear of sex or negative attitudes about sex (sex as in sexuality and/or sexual intercourse).
Acceptance of homosexuality as long as it remains a private issue.
Prejudice based on one's ethnicity.
Prejudice based on one's race.
Prejudice based on one's religious status.
Bias against one based on their status as obese.
A fear of strangers or foreigners.
A strong antipathy or aversion to strangers or foreigners.
Prejudice based on one's status as a foreigner; as a person from another land, state, or country.
Discrimination based on body weight.
Discrimination on the grounds of fatness.
Misogyny directed towards Black women where race and gender both play roles in bias.
Hatred of, contempt for, or prejudice against Black trans women.
Discrimination based on species membership or relationship.

A form of unjustified discrimination based on species membership. It involves treating members of one species as morally more important than members of other species even when their interests are equivalent. More precisely, speciesism is the failure to consider interests of equal strength to an equal extent because of the species of which the individuals have been classified as belonging to.
Discrimination based on a person's size.
Discrimination based on one's marital status.
Discrimination against and negative perception of single people.
A fear or hatred of religion, religious faith, religious people or religious organizations.
Fear or hatred of atheism or atheists.

A process in which persons improve their awareness and identity, evelop talents and potential, build human capital and facilitate employability, enhance the quality of life and contribute to the realization of dreams and aspirations. Personal development takes place over the course of a person's entire life.
The lifelong process of managing learning, work, leisure, and transitions in order to move toward a personally determined and evolving preferred future.
Progression upward over the course of an individual's career.
A situation in which a person has reached the highest level of their career possible.
